{{Infobox military unit | unit_name = 20th Mechanized Corps | dates = 1941 | country = [[Soviet Union]] | branch = [[Red Army]] | type = [[Mechanized corps (Soviet Union)|Mechanized corps]] | battles = [[World War II]] * [[Battle of Białystok–Minsk]] * [[Battle of Smolensk (1941)|Battle of Smolensk]] | notable_commanders = [[Nikolai Vedeneyev]] }}
The '''20th Mechanized Corps''' ([[Military Unit Number]] 2802)<ref name=":0" /> was a mechanized corps of the [[Red Army]]. Formed in March 1941, the corps was almost entirely destroyed in the [[Battle of Białystok–Minsk]] and the [[Battle of Smolensk (1941)|Battle of Smolensk]], in which it [[Siege of Mogilev|defended]] [[Mogilev]].
== History ==
=== Formation === [[File:Zerstörter T-26, Ostfeldzug.jpg|thumb|A destroyed [[T-26]] of the type used by the corps]] The 20th Mechanized Corps was formed in March and April 1941 from elements of the [[4th Cavalry Divison (Soviet Union)|4th Don Cossack Cavalry Division]] and the Borisov Automobile, Tank, and Cavalry Schools. Corps headquarters was located in [[Barysaw|Borisov]]. It included the [[26th Tank Division (Soviet Union)|26th]] and [[38th Tank Division (Soviet Union)|38th Tank Divisions]], and the [[210th Motorized Division (Soviet Union)|210th Motorized Division]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=http://mogilev-region.gov.by/page/20%C2%AD-i_mekhanizirovannyi_korpus_i_ego_rol_v_oborone_mogileva_letom_1941-%C2%ADgo_goda|title=20-Й МЕХАНИЗИРОВАННЫЙ КОРПУС И ЕГО РОЛЬ В ОБОРОНЕ МОГИЛЕВА ЛЕТОМ 1941-ГО ГОДА|last=Borisenko|first=Nikolai|date=2005|work=Mogilev Search Gazette|issue=3|language=Russian|trans-title=20th Mechanized Corps in the defense of Mogilev, summer 1941|access-date=20 August 2016|via=}}</ref> The 26th Tank Division was located at [[Krasnoye Urochishche]], the 38th Tank Division at [[Novoborisov]], and the 210th Motorized Division at [[Osipovichi]].<ref name=":0" /> The corps was commanded by Major General [[Andrey Grigorievich Nikitin|Andrei Nikitin]].{{Sfn|Glantz|2010|p=|pp=591{{endash}}592}}
=== Defense of Minsk area === On 22 June, Germany invaded the Soviet Union in [[Operation Barbarossa]]. The corps fought in the [[Battle of Białystok–Minsk]]. The corps was not yet fully formed and was at cadre strength.{{Sfn|Forczyk|2014|pp=30{{endash}}31}} Between 22 and 27 June the corps fought in battles in the [[Minsk]] area, unsuccessfully attempting to stop the German advance towards the city.{{Sfn|Forczyk|2014|p=52}} On 26 June it was ordered to conduct a counterattack with the [[4th Airborne Corps (Soviet Union)|4th Airborne Corps]] at [[Slutsk]]. The corps attacked with its 93 outdated light tanks (80 [[T-26]] tanks and 13 [[BT tank]]s)<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://mechcorps.rkka.ru/files/mechcorps/pages/20_meh.htm|title=20 механизированный корпус|last=Drig|first=Yevgeny|date=18 March 2009|website=mechcorps.rkka.ru|publisher=|language=Russian|trans-title=20th Mechanized Corps|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121215042946/http://mechcorps.rkka.ru/files/mechcorps/pages/20_meh.htm|archive-date=15 December 2012|access-date=20 August 2016}}</ref> and the 4th Airborne Corps advanced on foot instead of conducting an air assault due to a lack of transport aircraft. Both units were unable to stop the German advance.{{Sfn|Glantz|2010|pp=32, 38}} On 30 June the [[Svisloch]] Railroad Bridge, defended by the 4th Airborne Corps, was captured by the [[4th Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|4th Panzer Division]], cutting off most of the 20th Mechanized Corps and a 4th Airborne Corps brigade.{{Sfn|Glantz|2010|p=60}} The corps and other remnants of Soviet units delayed the advance of the [[XXXXVI Motorized Corps (Wehrmacht)|XXXXVI Motorized Corps]] with their resistance.{{Sfn|Glantz|2010|p=67}}
=== Defense of Mogilev === By 1 July it was part of the [[13th Army (Soviet Union)|13th Army]].{{Sfn|Glantz|2010|p=597}} On 7 July the corps included about 12,000 men with 27 guns and no tanks. From 9 to 27 July it fought in and was destroyed in the [[Mogilev]] pocket. By the end of 15 July the corps was defending Mogilev alongside the [[61st Rifle Corps]] and remnants of several divisions.{{Sfn|Glantz|2010|p=122}} On 21 July deputy corps commander Major General [[Nikolai Vedeneyev]] took command<ref>{{Ruheroes|id=3969|name=Nikolai Vedeneyev}}</ref> after Nikitin was wounded and evacuated. At this time the corps defended Mogilev's eastern approaches.{{Sfn|Glantz|2010|p=278}} By 25 July, the Soviet troops in Mogilev were running out of ammunition, food and fuel. 61st Rifle Corps commander [[Fyodor Bakunin]] made the decision to withdraw against orders{{Sfn|Glantz|2010|p=280}} and called a meeting with Vedeneyev and three of the division commanders on the breakout plan. The 20th Mechanized Corps would lead the breakout towards the general direction of [[Roslavl]].<ref name=":1" /> That night, the corps began the breakout. In the morning, the corps ran into the German [[78th Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|78th Infantry Division]] at the village of [[Samulki]]. Supported by vehicles from an attached reconnaissance battalion, the corps fought on foot and attacked the German positions. The attack was stopped by heavy German machine gun fire.<ref name=":1" /> Bakunin ordered the destruction of remaining equipment and ordered the survivors to disperse and break out in small groups.<ref name=":0" /> Between 27 and 28 July the corps broke out of the pocket with 100 to 200 men left. The ''perechen'' (list of Soviet units during World War II) does not state that the corps was disbanded,<ref>[http://www.teatrskazka.com/Raznoe/Perechni_voisk/Perechen_04_03.html Perechen No. 4 Part III]</ref> although it lost most of its men during the battles in the Mogilev Pocket.{{Sfn|Glantz|2010|p=|pp=591{{endash}}592}} The corps last appears on the [[combat composition of the Soviet Army]] list for 10 July 1941.<ref>[[Combat composition of the Soviet Army]], 10 July 1941, p. 23</ref>
